#compdef wuffs
# =============================================================================
# wuffs — Google's "Wuffs is a tool for managing Wuffs source code."
#         Wuffs (Wrangling Untrusted File Formats Safely) is a
#         memory-safe domain-specific programming language designed
#         SPECIFICALLY for writing parsers and decoders for untrusted
#         binary file formats (PNG, GIF, JPEG, WEBP, TIFF, BMP, JSON,
#         CBOR, ZIP, GZIP, ZLIB, DEFLATE, LZW, ZSTD, BROTLI, LZMA,
#         BZIP2, ADLER32, CRC32, MD5, SHA-256).  The Wuffs compiler
#         transpiles .wuffs source to plain C99 code that compiles
#         with any C compiler, with formal proofs that the generated
#         code:
#           - never has buffer overflows or underflows
#           - never has integer overflow / underflow / divide-by-zero
#           - never has unaligned reads / writes
#           - never has use-after-free or double-free (no malloc/free!)
#           - never has null-pointer dereferences
#           - never deadlocks
#           - terminates in bounded time for bounded input
#         Used in production by Chromium (PNG decoding), Skia (image
#         pipeline), Android (image codecs), and several security-
#         sensitive parsers in Google infrastructure.  The `wuffs`
#         command orchestrates source-to-C transpilation, runs the
#         Wuffs test suite, and benchmarks Wuffs decoders against
#         reference implementations (libpng, libjpeg-turbo, etc.).
#
# Author:  Nigel Tao and the Wuffs Authors at Google.  Nigel Tao is
#          also creator of Plan 9 from User Space contributor (with
#          Russ Cox), `purego` Go OpenGL bindings, and several other
#          systems-programming Go projects.  Wuffs development started
#          at Google in 2017, open-sourced shortly after.
# Source:  https://github.com/google/wuffs
# CLI:     cmd/wuffs/main.go (uses Go stdlib `flag` package with
#                              `flag.NewFlagSet` PER SUBCOMMAND +
#                              shared `cmd/commonflags` package
#                              defining common flags reused across
#                              subcommands)
# Library: Go stdlib `flag` + `google/wuffs/cmd/commonflags` shared-
#          flag module
#          (Wuffs's CLI is built on Go's stdlib flag package — same
#           foundation as yai R531 — but ADDS a SHARED-FLAG MODULE
#           PATTERN: `cmd/commonflags/commonflags.go` exports
#           `XxxDefault` and `XxxUsage` constants reused by each
#           subcommand's local flag.NewFlagSet — first documented
#           shared-flag-constants pattern across multiple subcommands)
# License: Apache-2.0 OR MIT
# Status:  Active — 4758+ stars on google/wuffs; Wuffs language is
#          at v0.4 (alpha) as of 2026; production codecs are in use
#          at Chromium / Skia / Android scale (billions of decodings
#          per day across Chrome users).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 67TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 67TH LANGUAGE — Wuffs.  Wuffs joins the corpus as a single-
# instance language (Wuffs=1) via its Go-driver `wuffs` orchestration
# binary using Go stdlib `flag` + shared `cmd/commonflags` module.
# Taxonomy now spans 276 cross-language CLI library variants across 67
# documented languages.
#
# Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=41 / Go=41 / TS-Node=41 (three-way tie
# at 41 preserved from R536).  Wuffs=1 (new — 67th language entry).
#
# This is the FIRST documented PARSER-FOCUSED MEMORY-SAFE DOMAIN-
# SPECIFIC LANGUAGE in the taxonomy.  Every other documented language
# (Rust, Go, Haskell, OCaml, Erlang, Ada, etc.) is a GENERAL-PURPOSE
# language that can be used for parsers among many other things.
# Wuffs is DESIGNED SPECIFICALLY for parsers and CANNOT be used for
# anything else.  Wuffs lacks:
#   - Dynamic memory allocation (no malloc, no GC, no heap)
#   - Standard library (no I/O, no networking, no threads)
#   - Mutable global state (no top-level mutable variables)
#   - Recursion (every function has a fixed call-depth bound)
#   - Floating-point (Wuffs is integer-only by design)
#   - String types (parsers work on byte slices)
#   - File I/O (caller supplies input buffer and output buffer)
# This is the FIRST documented language with such an aggressively-
# constrained semantics — a "BIG IDEA REDUCED" language where the
# SAFETY GUARANTEES come from what the language ABSENT-MINDEDLY
# REFUSES TO LET YOU EXPRESS.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R534/R535/R536 restoring three-way tie at
# 41 via lexopt/tview/blessed) followed by 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R537 THIS,
# Wuffs as 67th).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS WUFFS AND WHY IS IT THE 67TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Wuffs (https://github.com/google/wuffs, 4758+ stars) is **Google's
# "Wrangling Untrusted File Formats Safely" language** — created by
# Nigel Tao and the Wuffs Authors at Google in 2017.  Wuffs is a
# memory-safe domain-specific language SPECIFICALLY for writing
# parsers and decoders for untrusted binary file formats.
#
# Wuffs's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. STATIC PROOF OF SAFETY — Wuffs's compiler doesn't just CHECK
#      for memory-safety violations at runtime; it PROVES at compile
#      time that none can occur.  Every array access requires a
#      proof obligation that the index is within bounds.  Every
#      integer addition requires a proof that no overflow occurs.
#      Every iteration requires a proof that the loop terminates.
#      Wuffs's compiler is essentially a small theorem prover
#      specialized for parser invariants.  Compare:
#         * Rust:    borrow checker prevents some bugs at compile
#                    time; integer overflow is checked at runtime in
#                    debug builds; arrays panic at runtime on OOB
#         * Ada/SPARK: similar formal-proof approach but for general-
#                    purpose programs (not just parsers)
#         * Coq/Idris: full dependently-typed theorem provers
#                    (general purpose, slow proofs)
#      Wuffs's safety is the most AGGRESSIVE of any documented
#      language with practical compile times — proofs run in seconds.
#
#   2. TRANSPILES TO C99 — Wuffs source files (`.wuffs`) compile to
#      portable C99 code that integrates with existing C/C++/Rust
#      codebases.  The Wuffs compiler emits header + source pairs
#      that downstream projects link as-if regular C libraries.
#      Chromium's PNG decoder is literally Wuffs-generated C99 code
#      compiled into the Chromium binary.  Compare:
#         * Vyper (Ethereum) — compiles to EVM bytecode (one target)
#         * Cairo (Starkware) — compiles to STARK proofs (one target)
#         * Move (Sui/Aptos) — compiles to MoveVM (one target)
#         * Wuffs — compiles to PORTABLE C99 (one target but
#                    integrates with any platform with a C compiler)
#      Wuffs's choice of C99-as-target makes it UNIQUELY portable
#      among documented "safety-focused" DSLs.
#
#   3. NO STANDARD LIBRARY — Wuffs has no `print`, no `malloc`, no
#      `read_file`, no `string` type, no `Vec<T>`, no `HashMap`.
#      Parser functions take a `slice u8` input buffer + `slice u8`
#      output buffer as arguments; the caller (in C/C++/Rust)
#      provides ALL I/O.  This is the absolute MINIMAL parser-only
#      surface area.  Compare:
#         * Rust:    `std` is opt-in but available
#         * Go:      stdlib is always available
#         * Haskell: Prelude is implicit
#      Wuffs is the FIRST documented language with NO STANDARD
#      LIBRARY AT ALL.
#
#   4. NO DYNAMIC ALLOCATION — Wuffs has no `malloc`, no `new`, no
#      heap.  Every data structure is stack-allocated or caller-
#      provided.  This is necessary for the compile-time safety
#      proofs (proving freedom from use-after-free is trivial when
#      `free` doesn't exist).  Compare every other documented
#      language which HAS a heap allocator.  FIRST documented
#      heap-free language in the taxonomy.
#
#   5. NO RECURSION — Wuffs functions cannot recurse.  Every call
#      graph is a DAG with a known maximum depth.  This makes
#      Wuffs's call-stack bounded at compile time (no stack
#      overflow possible).  Compare Rust which can recurse with
#      potential stack overflow, OCaml which has tail-call
#      optimization, Haskell which uses lazy evaluation to avoid
#      recursion-as-loop costs.  Wuffs is the FIRST documented
#      recursion-free language.
#
#   6. NO FLOATING-POINT — Wuffs uses integer arithmetic only.  No
#      `f32`, no `f64`, no `double`.  Parsers don't need floating-
#      point and Wuffs's design enforces this.  Audio/video codec
#      writers compile away DCT (discrete cosine transform) via
#      fixed-point integer arithmetic with explicit precision
#      analysis at compile time.  FIRST documented integer-only
#      language in the taxonomy.
#
#   7. NO STRINGS — Wuffs has no `string` type.  Text parsers work
#      on `slice u8` byte slices with explicit decoding via UTF-8
#      iterators or other format-specific encodings.  This forces
#      explicit decisions about encoding rather than implicit UTF-8
#      assumptions.  FIRST documented language with NO STRING TYPE.
#
# Wuffs's relationship to other documented languages:
#
#   * Like Ada/SPARK     — formal-proof-of-safety approach
#   * Like Move (Sui)     — designed for safety in adversarial context
#   * Like Idris / Coq    — uses theorem proving (but specialized)
#   * Like C99 (transpile target) — compiles to portable C
#   * Like Vyper / Move    — DSL targeting a specific runtime
#   * Unlike all of the above — designed SPECIFICALLY for binary
#                                parsers with NO standard library,
#                                NO heap, NO recursion, NO floats,
#                                NO strings.  Wuffs's "language
#                                minimalism" is the most aggressive
#                                of any documented language.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE `wuffs` CLI — Go stdlib `flag` + Shared `cmd/commonflags` Module
#
# The `wuffs` driver binary is written in Go (not Wuffs itself — the
# language doesn't have stdlib for things like argv parsing or file
# I/O).  Its CLI uses Go stdlib `flag` with `flag.NewFlagSet` PER
# SUBCOMMAND:
#
#     // cmd/wuffs/main.go
#     var commands = []struct {
#         name string
#         do   func(wuffsRoot string, args []string) error
#     }{
#         {"bench", doBench},
#         {"gen", doGen},
#         {"genlib", doGenlib},
#         {"test", doTest},
#     }
#
# Each subcommand has its own flag set:
#
#     // cmd/wuffs/test.go
#     flags := flag.NewFlagSet(`"wuffs test <flags> std/pkg1 std/pkg2 etc"`, flag.ExitOnError)
#     ccompilersFlag := flags.String("ccompilers", cf.CcompilersDefault, cf.CcompilersUsage)
#     focusFlag := flags.String("focus", cf.FocusDefault, cf.FocusUsage)
#     langsFlag := flags.String("langs", langsDefault, langsUsage)
#     mimicFlag := flags.Bool("mimic", cf.MimicDefault, cf.MimicUsage)
#     skipgenFlag := flags.Bool("skipgen", skipgenDefault, skipgenUsage)
#     skipgendepsFlag := flags.Bool("skipgendeps", skipgendepsDefault, skipgendepsUsage)
#
# The `cf` import is `github.com/google/wuffs/cmd/commonflags` —
# a SHARED-FLAG MODULE that exports default values and usage
# strings reused across subcommands.  This pattern is rare among
# Go CLI tools:
#
#     // cmd/commonflags/commonflags.go (excerpt)
#     const (
#         CcompilersDefault = "clang,gcc"
#         CcompilersUsage   = `comma-separated list of C compilers`
#         FocusDefault = ""
#         FocusUsage   = `comma-separated list of tests or
#                         benchmarks (name prefixes) to focus on`
#         ...
#     )
#
# This is the FIRST documented CLI library variant that uses a
# SHARED-FLAG-CONSTANTS MODULE across multiple subcommand flag sets,
# avoiding the typical Go pattern of duplicating flag definitions or
# using a global cobra/urfave-cli registration.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go-flag-stdlib usage on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. SHARED-FLAG-CONSTANTS MODULE — Every other documented Go CLI
#      using `flag` (yai R531, anything else using stdlib flag)
#      defines flags inline.  Wuffs has a `cmd/commonflags` package
#      that exports `XxxDefault` + `XxxUsage` constants reused
#      across `bench`, `gen`, `genlib`, `test` subcommands.  FIRST
#      documented Go CLI library with a shared-flag-constants
#      module.
#
#   2. SUBCOMMAND-LOCAL `flag.NewFlagSet` — Every other documented
#      Go CLI library either uses one global flag set (cobra style)
#      or struct-tags (go-arg style).  Wuffs's pattern is
#      DELIBERATE: each subcommand creates its own `flag.NewFlagSet`
#      with subcommand-specific name, instantiates flags it needs
#      from the shared module, and parses argv[1:] (after stripping
#      the subcommand name).  FIRST documented Go pattern with
#      explicit per-subcommand flag.NewFlagSet construction.
#
#   3. NO SHELL-COMPLETION INTEGRATION — Every other documented
#      Go CLI library auto-generates shell completions via cobra's
#      `genzshcomp` or urfave-cli's autocomplete templates.  Wuffs
#      has NO completion system — completions like this one are
#      hand-written by users.  FIRST documented Go CLI library
#      with zero completion-generation support.
#
#   4. STRING-BASED LANGUAGE LIST FLAG — `-langs="c,go,rs"` is a
#      comma-separated list of target languages that the Wuffs
#      transpiler emits.  This list is validated at runtime against
#      `[a-z0-9]+` regex pattern.  Every other documented Go CLI
#      library uses repeated-flag style (`-l c -l go -l rs`).  FIRST
#      documented Go CLI library with comma-separated list flag.
#
#   5. NO ENV VAR FALLBACK — Every other documented Go CLI library
#      (cobra, urfave/cli, kong, go-arg) supports falling back to
#      env vars when flags are not set.  Wuffs has zero env-var
#      integration — every flag must be explicitly set on argv or
#      uses the hardcoded default.  FIRST documented Go CLI library
#      with no env-var fallback.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/google/wuffs/blob/main/cmd/wuffs/main.go +
# bench.go + gen.go + test.go +
# https://github.com/google/wuffs/blob/main/cmd/commonflags/commonflags.go )
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'bench:benchmark packages (compare Wuffs decoders to mimics)'
    'gen:generate C/Go/Rust source code from .wuffs packages'
    'genlib:generate compiled libraries (.a / .so / .dll) from .wuffs packages'
    'test:run unit tests on Wuffs packages'
    'help:show help for a specific subcommand'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'wuffs subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            bench)
                _arguments -s \
                    '-ccompilers=[comma-separated list of C compilers (default clang,gcc)]:compilers:' \
                    '-focus=[comma-separated list of benchmark name prefixes to focus on]:prefixes:' \
                    '-iterscale=[scaling factor for iterations per benchmark (default 100)]:scale:' \
                    '-mimic[compare Wuffs output to other libraries (libpng, libjpeg, etc.)]' \
                    '-reps=[repetitions per benchmark (default 5)]:reps:' \
                    '*:Wuffs package:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            gen)
                _arguments -s \
                    '-ccompilers=[comma-separated list of C compilers]:compilers:' \
                    '-genlinenum[generate filename:line_number comments in output]' \
                    '-langs=[comma-separated list of target languages (file extensions, e.g. "c,go,rs"; default "c")]:langs:' \
                    '-skipgendeps[skip automatically generating package dependencies]' \
                    '*:Wuffs package:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            genlib)
                _arguments -s \
                    '-ccompilers=[comma-separated list of C compilers]:compilers:' \
                    '-langs=[comma-separated list of target languages]:langs:' \
                    '-skipgendeps[skip generating dependencies]' \
                    '-version=[version string (e.g. "1.2.3-beta.4")]:version:' \
                    '*:Wuffs package:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            test)
                _arguments -s \
                    '-ccompilers=[comma-separated list of C compilers]:compilers:' \
                    '-focus=[comma-separated list of test name prefixes to focus on]:prefixes:' \
                    '-langs=[comma-separated list of target languages]:langs:' \
                    '-mimic[compare Wuffs output to other libraries]' \
                    '-skipgen[skip automatically generating code before testing]' \
                    '-skipgendeps[skip generating dependencies]' \
                    '*:Wuffs package:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            help)
                _describe -t commands 'wuffs subcommand' commands && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
